Instructions
*************************************************************************************************************************

mDES takes 4 command line arguments (only tested in this order):
----------------------------------------------------------------

-e / -d							-> tells the program to encrypt or decrypt
plaintext as hex characters		-> the plaintext or ciphertext depending on the previous -e/-d argument
-k								-> indicates the next argument is the 8-bit key to use
key								-> the 8-bit encryption key used to generate the round keys, as two hex characters

Note that the input is assumed to be multiples of 8-bit blocks (two hex characters) and already padded if necessary.


Examples:
---------

Input:		>> ./mDES -e 0123456789abcdef -k 4d         -> tells the program to encrypt "0123456789abcdef" using key "4d"
Output:     Set to encrypt   							-> running in encryption mode
			Plaintext:		0x0123456789abcdef			-> plaintext in hex
			Key: 			0x4d 						-> key used in hex
			Ciphertext: 	0x231404152de00222			-> resulting ciphertext in hex

Input:		>> ./mDES -d 231404152de00222 -k 4d			-> tells the program to decrypt "231404152de00222" using key "4d" 
Output:		Set to decrypt								-> running in encryption mode
			Ciphertext:	0x231404152de00222				-> ciphertext in hex
			Key: 		0x4d 							-> key used in hex
			Plaintext: 	0x0123456789abcdef				-> resulting plaintext in hex

*************************************************************************************************************************
